What is Permissions Boundary?

Permissions Boundary is an IAM policy that sets the maximum permissions an IAM user or role can have. 
Even if their IAM policy grants full admin, the boundary restricts them to only what the boundary allows — preventing privilege escalation.

It is a policy that sets the maximum permissions an IAM user or role can have — even if their IAM policy allows more.

Simple Analogy

IAM Policy  =  What you ARE allowed to do
Permissions Boundary = Maximum LIMIT you cannot exceed

Example:
  IAM Policy says      → can do S3, EC2, RDS, Lambda
  Permissions Boundary → max allowed is S3 and EC2 only

  Final Permission     → only S3 and EC2 ✅
                         RDS and Lambda blocked ❌

---------------------
How It Works

IAM Policy        ∩        Permissions Boundary
(what is allowed)     (what is the max limit)
        │
        ▼
   Final Permission
   (intersection of both)

----
Permissions Boundary vs SCP

SCP                          Permissions Boundary
────────────────────         ────────────────────
Applies to AWS Account       Applies to IAM User/Role
Set by Management Account    Set by Admin in same account
Controls entire account      Controls individual user/role
Even root cannot bypass      Root user not affected
AWS Organizations needed     No Organizations needed

---------------------
Real Example
Without Permissions Boundary

Developer IAM Policy → Full Admin Access
                     → can create any resource
                     → can escalate own privileges ❌ DANGEROUS
----------------
With Permissions Boundary

Admin sets Permissions Boundary on Developer:
  → Max allowed: S3 + EC2 only

Developer IAM Policy says: Full Admin
Permissions Boundary says: S3 + EC2 only

Final Permission: S3 + EC2 only ✅
Developer CANNOT escalate privileges
-------------
Create Permissions Boundary

{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "s3:*",
        "ec2:*"
      ],
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}
---------------
All 3 Policies Together

SCP                          → Account level limit
    │
    ▼
Permissions Boundary         → User/Role level limit
    │
    ▼
IAM Policy                   → Actual permissions
    │
    ▼
Final Permission = intersection of all 3
-----------------
Key Points

✅ Only applies to IAM users and roles
✅ Does NOT grant permissions — only limits
✅ Admin sets it — user cannot remove it
✅ Prevents privilege escalation
✅ No AWS Organizations needed
