What are the use cases of Permissions Boundary?

Permissions Boundary is mainly used to prevent privilege escalation, enable safe developer self-service, 
and limit blast radius during security incidents. It ensures that even if an IAM policy grants broad access, 
users and roles stay within the defined maximum boundary

1. Prevent Privilege Escalation (Most Common)

Problem:
  Developer has Admin access
  Developer creates a new IAM user
  Gives that user Full Admin
  → Developer escalated privileges ❌

Solution with Boundary:
  Set boundary on Developer
  → Developer CANNOT create user
    with more permissions than boundary allows
  → Privilege escalation blocked ✅

2. Safe Developer Self-Service

Problem:
  Developers need to create IAM roles
  for their Lambda/EC2 applications
  But giving them IAM full access is risky

Solution:
  Set boundary → Developers can create roles
  BUT created roles cannot exceed boundary
  → Developers get freedom ✅
  → Security maintained ✅

3. Contractor / Third Party Access

Problem:
  You hire a contractor to work on S3
  You don't want them touching EC2, RDS
  But their company gives them broad access

Solution:
  Set boundary on contractor's IAM role
  → Max allowed: S3 only
  → Cannot touch EC2, RDS, Lambda ✅

4. Multi Team Environment

DevOps Team    → Boundary allows EC2, EKS, S3
Dev Team       → Boundary allows Lambda, S3, DynamoDB
Security Team  → Boundary allows IAM, CloudTrail, Config
Data Team      → Boundary allows S3, Glue, Athena, Redshift

Each team stays in their lane ✅

5. CI/CD Pipeline Roles

Problem:
  Jenkins/GitHub Actions role needs
  broad permissions to deploy
  But you don't want it touching IAM

Solution:
  Set boundary on pipeline role
  → Can deploy EC2, EKS, Lambda
  → Cannot create/modify IAM ✅
  → Pipeline compromise = limited blast radius

Your Real World Context

Your EKS setup at GlobalPayments:

Jenkins role → Boundary set
  ✅ Can deploy to EKS
  ✅ Can push to ECR
  ✅ Can read S3
  ❌ Cannot modify IAM
  ❌ Cannot touch RDS
  ❌ Cannot access billing

→ Even if Jenkins is compromised
  attacker cannot escalate privileges

